In [ ]:
original_dir = pathlib.Path("../data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats/train")
new_base_dir = pathlib.Path("../data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats_small")

def make_subset(subset_name, start_index, end_index):
    for category in ("cat", "dog"):
        dir = new_base_dir / subset_name / category
        os.makedirs(dir)
        fnames = [f"{category}.{i}.jpg" for i in range(start_index, end_index)]
        for fname in fnames:
            shutil.copyfile(src=original_dir / fname,
                            dst=dir / fname)

make_subset("train", start_index=0, end_index=1000)
make_subset("validation", start_index=1000, end_index=1500)
make_subset("test", start_index=1500, end_index=2500)

for file_name in os.listdir('../data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats/train') :
    if re.findall("\Acat", file_name) :
        class_name = 'cat'
    else :
        class_name = 'dog'
    temp_df.append((os.path.join('../data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats/train', file_name), class_name))

#create data frame df     
df = pd.DataFrame(temp_df, columns=['file_path', 'label'])

def plot_6_image(images, title) :
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 3))
    for i, path in enumerate(images) :
        plt.subplot(1, 6, i+1)
        img = cv2.imread(path)
        plt.imshow(img)
        plt.axis('off')
    plt.suptitle(title, fontsize=20, fontweight='bold')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
        
# Setting the random seed for reproducibility
np.random.seed(42)

for classes in ['cat', 'dog'] :
    temp_df = df.file_path[df.label==classes]
    random_image = np.random.choice(temp_df, 6)
    plot_6_image(random_image, classes)

Let's check the max and min dimensions of images:

In [ ]:
def image_size(train_folder) :
    height = []
    width = []
    
    unique_dims = set()
    
    for file_name in os.listdir(train_folder) :
        img_path = os.path.join(train_folder, file_name)
        img = cv2.imread(img_path)
        if img is not None :
            unique_dims.add((img.shape[0], img.shape[1]))
            #
            width.append(img.shape[0])
            height.append(img.shape[1])

    if len(unique_dims)==1 :
        print(f'All images have a unique shape of {list(unique_dims)[0]}')
    else :
        print(f'There are {len(unique_dims)} different image dimensions')
        print(f'Min height is {min(height)}, Min width is {min(width)}')
        print(f'Max height is {max(height)}, Max width is {max(width)}')

image_size('../data/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats/train')

Train two networks:¶

Neural Network (CNN):

In [ ]:
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(180, 180, 3))                            
x = layers.Rescaling(1./255)(inputs)                                 
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.Flatten()(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)
model = keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)

In this convnet, we will see a progressive increase in the model from 32 to 256.
We divide by 255 to change range from 0 - 255 to 0 - 1.
This is just like a binary classification problem where at the end the model has a single unit which is a Dense layer of size 1, and a sigmoid activation. It will encode the probability that the model is looking at one class or the other.

Fine Tunning VGG-16:¶

Steps:

  • Download model (VGG)
  • Freeze layers
  • Define and train model
  • (For fine-tuning) unfreeze some layers in the base network.
  • Evaluate the model

Freezing a layer or set of layers prevents their weights from being updated during training.

In [ ]:
conv_base = keras.applications.vgg16.VGG16(
    weights="imagenet",
    include_top=False,
    input_shape=(180, 180, 3))

Downloading data from https://storage.googleapis.com/tensorflow/keras-applications/vgg16/vgg16_weights_tf_dim_ordering_tf_kernels_notop.h5

In [ ]:
conv_base.trainable = False #FREEZE layers
In [ ]:
data_augmentation = keras.Sequential(
    [
        layers.RandomFlip("horizontal"),
        layers.RandomRotation(0.1),
        layers.RandomZoom(0.2),
    ]
)
#define input
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(180, 180, 3)) 
x = data_augmentation(inputs)
#preprocessing
x = keras.applications.vgg16.preprocess_input(x) 
x = conv_base(x)
x = layers.Flatten()(x) 
#fully connected with previous layer
x = layers.Dense(256)(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)
#chain that starts from input and goes till the output
model1 = keras.Model(inputs, outputs)

    keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(

        monitor="val_loss")
]

    train_dataset,
    epochs=30,
    validation_data=validation_dataset,

Conclusion:¶

After checking the accuracy, precision, recall and f1-score, we conclude that the accuracy of CNN neural network performs better than the VGG fine-tuned model.
CNN gave us better accuracy of almost 73% where as the best parameter values we could get after VGG16-fined tuning was 68%. Therefore, we for our dataset dog vs cat, we can use the model which gives us better performance which in this case is CNN.
